text: They ran out of ideas. That's why they adapted something instead of making original stories. The developer has nothing makes him to say something, just another adaptation. Because the hollywood Ghost in the Shell had failed, I didn't watch Alita. But I didn't know how bad this one can be.     Everyone said it's good mostly because she is female. Just like "Time to have a female president!" Not its story telling skill like descriptive trick or the duality of a character, even a side character. The doctor (I'm not sure about the name. I didn't read it in English.) found Gally at night, not some kind of stupid morning to present hope and start. Nobody found her. He is the only one found her, and she belongs to him alone. He is the only one she can count on.     A woman was murdered. The woman was smoking, so it focused on her arm, beautiful arm. The very next day Gally has a pair of beautiful arms. The good stuff that the doctor is impossible to find in the crap yard. Then the doc promises the sleeping (He thinks so) Gally that he'll make her perfect while he is wearing coat to cover himself to go out at night. Gally is happy to have legs to make herself go out on her own, and it is the moment that she notices that women were murdered at night by warning, like cold water poured on her when she is happy. When something good happened, there is also something bad happening. She notices that doc has new wound on arm, since it's new she assumes it was caused last night, the night before the day that doc has found the legs for her. And this night Gally has her own legs to move to take action on her mind. The dark side of human. Just like the ancestor of human being is naturally hunting other creatures to feed his child to make her better.     And all of these was just ruined in the movie, since Alita got that fancy ivory color whole body in the beginning. Thanks, American. You sucessfully turned a Japanese art into an american child education. "I was born special! I can do whatever I want if I do! By the way, I'm also a female." People who can not tell it just follow the advertisement, and the story encourages them, "Be Yourself". What a contradiction.

text: I have never made a comment before about anything on YouTube, or anything on the web really tbh. I saw this movie, and couldn’t believe how blow away I was by it. I read the manga. But that wasn’t just the reason I loved it. I’m 34 and I have seen many movies in my life. Some terrible, some ok and some amazing! This movie was amazing! I believe that I know what a great movie is without listening to critics reviews. This movie gave me the same feelings I got when I first saw avatar, Independence Day and Jurassic park. Movies can make you feel so many things when it’s done right! Not every movie make me feel That way when I watch them. That’s how I knew this was a one of a kind! Do yourself a favor and watch this movie to show it the support it truly deserves! I’m hoping on a sequel to be made!

text: A shout-out to the film makers. Not only in this an incredibly well done movie, it's also a fantastic film that works by itself. This film has it all. Kickass action, next level CGI, a great set of characters, heart and depth. I've watched it 5 times by now and each time I notice more and more details that make this movie so rich and Alita such an awesome, rounded and lovable character. And the fight scenes just don't get old. It's extremely rewatchable not just for moments when the **** starts hitting the fan, but I also love the slower, more character focused moments.   I'll keep watching it in the cinema for as long as I still have the chance to, and I can't wait to pick up the bluray whenever it comes out.   And we NEED a sequel!!!

text: I find it really funny, that cameron decided to make some changes to the story just to make it more dramatic for some reason:  -SPOILER ALERT-  . .  .  .  .  .  .  Like Alita's name. It wasn't name of his deceased daughter (btw, Ido didn't have a wife and didn't remove his mark of Zalem), but of his cat.  Or how berserker's body was found. Ido found it years ago, examined it and became furious after he discovered that it was pretty much a weapon meant to turn people into killing machines. He locked it up in his basement and after body he gave Alita was destroyed in her first fight against Makaku (where teh hell did he get Gervishka, what?), he gave it to her, so she can protect herself.  Or how Panzer-Kunst was first mentioned. In the manga Ido mentioned it when Alita fought the mutant who was killing the women (not big bad robots).  Or how she became hunter-warrior. Alita was mad at Ido that he was treating her like his dress-up doll and ran off to the Factory to get her mark of the Hunter. In the movie she goes there with hugo - who in manga doesn't appear until after her fight with makaku.  Makaku/Gervishka was not protected by zalem, he was a long-time wanted criminal, but too many hunter warriors died after trying to kill him, so every hunter warrior was reluctant to give it a go. Speech about fighting makaku/gervishka was much less dramatic and was given by Ido after he goes to Kansas bar with Alita for the first time.   As for motorball, there was a timeskip in the manga before she was in 2nd league, but it was a nice touch that they've shown how it started for her - playing with other kids on the street. What I didn't like was removal of her coach and technican guy.   Makaku/Gervishka didn't get grind cutters installed by zalem "baddies", he got them by literally ripping Colloseum's (popular sport on other end of Scrapyard, rivaling M0torball in popularity) head off his body and installing himself there.  There were many more minor changes in this movie that differ it's story from the manga which made it quite irritating for me to watch it.  .  .   .  Tl;dr: Movie differs from the manga so it can be more dramatic and more appealing to americans. Weird, because manga itself is a classic, full of black humor which I bet would appear to cyberpunk fans and teens alike.  If you read the manga and expect decent adaptaion of the story, don't watch it. If you didn't, go ahead. It's nothing amazing, but it will keep you entertained.

text: I remember watching this trailer when I was about to watch another movie with my mother at the cinema. I thought the graphics looked good so I’d watch it, that’s it. Nothing special.  But yesterday I went to see this movie in Glasgow in IMAX, and let me tell you I was not disappointed in the slightest.   This movie exceeded all of my expectations. Even for the best movies, I usually find myself at some part losing track and wondering if the movie is going to end soon because X or Y reasons. But here, not even once. You’re born with Alita, you live and suffer her pain, you fight with her. You want to see her prosper and reach her goal just as much as she does. I’m not exaggerating. Besides the scenes that were absolutely breathtaking (can we talk about the first camera shots of the motoball game? Mesmerising), Alita herself gave more emotions than I believe any human actor could. Through the lenses of a cyborg you see more humanity than a human could ever show you.  I sincerely hope there will be a Sequel. That ending was absolutely brutal, and it pains me to know that because of lack of audiences she might not be given a proper ending. If you’re hesitating, please go! You don’t realise what you’re missing out.

My only desapointment would be that it would have made such a perfect series to work even more on the complex story that Yukito Kishiro made. But with a 200 million dollars investment on the 2 hours movie I can get why it wasn't made. text: Great adaptation. Makes you wish it was longer than it is. You don't want the immersion to end, you want the film to continue. And this is from a person who has both read the manga and watched the animation. They have intricately woven this amazing looking world using the core of the source material itself so it looks and feels real. The character is someone you know: It is you that are trying to discover who you are and your roots, but at the same integrate your journey of discovery to your newfound self. Alita is and knows a lot, but it never stops her from becoming more and learning more; of a friend, a lover, a sibling and an older sister, a soldier and a leader. She has always been a growth minded character in the manga and the film does not fail to recognise that. That's the main reason I liked the film. Well... that and the stunning imax experience that I had tasted for the first time. I'm very glad it was a meaningful film like this and not a run-of-the-mill superhero flick.

I suspect this will have a somewhat comparable fate.

text: I understand this is an adaptation, and the movie hasn't been released yet, but I'm worried it won't be faithful to the manga.  here's the list of differences I think I spotted. -Vector was never a full on villain in the manga, he was just a morally grey black market dealer who controlled supply lines to the scrapyard and Tiphares/Zalem. He was integral to Hugo's character development, but after that he became a reoccurring character. -The big guy with the saw blade fingers was a villain that acted independently, and was never connected to Vector. -The character Chiren is not a character in the manga, she's from the non-cannon 1993 OVA -The woman with the blade hands also is not from the manga -Zapan is also not associated with Vecter, he's a lone wolf bounty hunter (called Hunter Warriors in the story) that comes into conflict with Alita/Gally due to them pursuing the same target. (can't say anything more because there's spoilers). -Ido found and was holding onto the berserker body long before Alita/Gally showed up. He knew exactly what it was and knew it was dangerous. -In the manga, Alita/Gally destroys her "first" body when facing off against Makaku (saw blade fingers) for the first time, and she goes to the bar to ask the hunter warriors for help (which is also when Zapan is introduced) , and by then she has the berserker body. It doesn't seem like this is the case in the movie.  The manga is one of my all time favorites (I read all of Gunnm, Gunnm Last Order, and what was so far released for Gunnm Mars Chronicle in three days), and I wouldn't have found out about it were it not for the movie adaptation. This is an adaptation and I do believe adaptations should be able to stand on their own, no matter how close to the source material they are, I just hope that the movie isn't hurt by these story differences.

text: Either way, a bunch of people are going to complain "It's not like the comic! That didn't happen! Blah blah blah blah." No movie is ever like the book. Movies based on books should be viewed exactly as such, something that is *based* on a book, not something that is a complete paper to screen conversion. If you need to, veiw the movie as something completely different that just borrowed some ideas. No movie will ever live up to the book. The only one that came close to including as much stuff as possible and stayed as true as possible was probably The Lord Of The Rings trilogy. LOTR spanned over 4 hours, and was still nowhere near the book.

text: I'm not that put off by the eyes, I'm more put off that she doesn't look real at all. CGI has yet to (and probably never will) master rendering humans realistically enough to make them seamless with real actors on set. And since pretty much everyone else in this film is actually there (minus the other pretty obvious cyborg characters she fights) I'd watch this and constantly see that she isn't actually there. She really does look like a full anime character plonked right in the middle of a live action film and its very jarring.

text: Getting a bit fed up of outlets covering this movie by saying that the fans of the original manga are "outraged about the size of her eyes". Im willing to bet my life the ones complaining have not only never read an original manga but have probably only got Dragonball or something similar as a reference. James Cameron decided to keep her design inkeeping with the original manga because he is a fan. Im a fan of the 80s & 90s manga because its what i grew up with and i think the look of Alita is amazing. Notice most human characters have augmented theyre bodies in some way but theyre heads are normal. This is how its represented in the original artwork. Yet Alita has these exaggerated eyes! This is because she is completely artificial except one internal organ her brain! So her whole body including her skull is artificial. Its not that hard a concept to grasp is it?

text: The most obvious complaint someone would have with this is the main character has to be the one that has enormous eyes and a completely terribly looking animated face, the only one.   It seems like a lot of different cuts from different parts of the movie are included, so either they've shown honestly too much of the action, or some of those scenes won't be in the movie and the trailer is attempting to draw attention by flashing some budget in your face.   I understand a main character being the center of attention, but this doesn't seem like a movie that will reward any other character for existing except the one who's name is the title. The whole trailer seemed to be stroking off the idea of how cool and rockin' this character is, showin' off all these sick tricks n' stunts yo. Honestly, makes me believe there's no compelling story to be shown, no characters to choose your favorites from.

text: Wow.. The comments divide into categories: - It's Cameron! Hype! - It's Linkin park! Hype! - Anime eyes! Mixed reaction. - Cyberpunk 2077! (oO WTF!)  When in actuality it is a very lame adaptation of a great complex story in a gritty, visceral and very cynical dystopian setting of GUNNM (Battle Angel Alita) MANGA, boasting superb storytelling and world building, character development, moral dilemmas and absolutely glorious visual tech design. All of which seems to have gone down the drain in the PG-13 movie. Anime adaptation went a very different way and was closed after 2 episodes, so if you only watched it, better read the manga. Movie seems to go the same way anime did, so you can just as well go read manga already =D

text: CHALMERS: Well, Seymour, I made it... despite your directions. SKINNER: Ah, Superintendent Chalmers! Welcome! I hope you're prepared for an unforgettable luncheon! CHALMERS: Uhh... SKINNER: [gasp] Oh egads, my roast is ruined! But what if... I were to purchase fast food and disguise it as my own cooking? [to himself] Oh ho ho ho ho... delightfully devilish, Seymour! CHALMERS: Uh- [cue song] Skinner with his crazy explanations, The superintendent's gonna need his medication, When he hears Skinner's lame exaggerations, There'll be trouble in town tonight! [end of song] CHALMERS: Seymour! SKINNER: Superintendent, I was just, uh... just stretching my calves on the windowsill. Isometric exercise! Care to join me? CHALMERS: Why is there smoke coming out of your oven, Seymour? SKINNER: Uhh... no! That isn't smoke. It's steam. Steam from the steamed clams we're having! Mmm... steamed clams! [beat] Ooh... [a few moments later] SKINNER: Superintendent, I hope you're ready for mouthwatering hamburgers! CHALMERS: I thought we were having steamed clams. SKINNER: D'oh, no. I said steamed hams! That's what I call hamburgers! CHALMERS: You call hamburgers "steamed hams?" SKINNER: Yes. It's a regional dialect! CHALMERS: Uh-huh... uh, what region? SKINNER: Uhh... upstate New York? CHALMERS: Really? Well, I'm from Utica, and I've never heard anyone use the phrase "steamed hams." SKINNER: Oh, not in Utica, no. It's an Albany expression. CHALMERS: I see. [beat] You know, these hamburgers are quite similar to the ones they have at Krusty Burger. SKINNER: Oh ho ho ho... no, patented Skinner burgers. Old family recipe. CHALMERS: For steamed hams? SKINNER: Yes. CHALMERS: Yeah, so you call them "steamed hams" despite the fact they are obviously grilled. SKINNER: Ye- hey- you know, the- one thing I should- excuse me for one second. CHALMERS: Of course. SKINNER: [YAWN] Well, that was wonderful. A good time was had by all, I'm pooped. CHALMERS: Yes, I should be- Good Lord, what is happening in there!? SKINNER: Aurora borealis? CHALMERS: Uh- aurora borealis!? At this time of year, at this time of day, in this part of the country, localized entirely within your kitchen!? SKINNER: Yes! CHALMERS: May I see it? SKINNER: No. SKINNER'S MOTHER: Seymour, the house is on fire! SKINNER: No, mother—it's just the northern lights! CHALMERS: Well, Seymour, you are an odd fellow, but I must say... you steam a good ham. SKINNER'S MOTHER: Help! Help

text: I know people are going to gripe about the changes, but really some things that work in comics dont float so well in movies. Usually when producing a largely visual spectacle action flick, they need to simplify the emotional and intellectual aspects to keep the tone consistent. It's going to be weird for me if Alita doesnt crack one liners under her breath, but it would probabaly worse if she did. Action movies often cant allow characters to grow in too many directions. It exhausts the audience and muddles the character objectives. I just hope that they keep her characterization consistent with the manga. Alita as a person does not continually fall back on male characters during her growth. She doesnt "need" anyone to continue to move forward. It's a very feminist theme that I hope translates well in the film. TLDR: have problems, still will see.

No blood (lets not even start on brain splatter) , no doctor nova in sight, no jeru tatoo on Ido, streets cleaner than actual slums, there is now a large heavenly forest instead of a deadly desert, which question the point of living in Zalem. Ifthe Scrapyard is a nice city to live in, most of gunnm identy is missing. You don't need hunter warriors, you don't need motorball, and yugo or the Barjack has no point anymore.   I guess whats left wont interest me :'(

text: Hm... I'm not convinced. It smells a bit of the same trappings GitS fell into. In the original story Gally/Alita was a "nobody" at first. She wasn't recognized as special by others untill she started to make a name of her own (and attract attention). Here it looks like your standard run-of-the-mill "you're the cornerstone of everything special" kind of plot.   Don't get me wrong, I'm not saying you have to copy-paste the manga; but you should be aware what the sotry is centered around and what makes each character's... well, character be what it is. They have archs that depend on that. Even more, here I see the absense of Desty Nova... and it troubbles me. Nova is the one who "makes" Gally/Alita special in many ways. It's his obsession with karma that makes him attracted to the tragic character that's Gally/Alita and he drives many of her transformations trough antagonism and pressure (not all of her archs, of course). She's not special because (SPOILERS!!!!!)...   ...she's a Martian supersoldier tech-wise, but because she has all the accumulated tragedy and karma that comes with. But she's also special because she's a good person (or wants to be one) in a world that's really shitty.   This looks too much like a standard plot where everyone wants to get her because she's the McGuffin and at the same time she's the only possible hope for everyone, because she's the McGuffin filled special saiviour.   I really hope I'm wrong, because, creepy eyes aside (why only she?... this element makes no sense world building wise), it looks decent enough.

text: A cross between live action and animation, not bad...it could have been fantastic if it were fully animated but the animators put in their best efforts than acting like the rest and not bother with the look...it still looks like a 3-D animated film with barely enough live action scenes, but the best part about this film is that Rodriguez actually made a 3-D film look good...also the script's okay and we know James Cameron wrote it. If I were writing the script, I'd concentrate on the story of the manga than the anime. If I were directing, I'd ask the animators to be creative and make a fight scene that looked cool and complex to them, and pretty much make it a fully animated film because what's the point in dragging actors in the film studio when their performances would be layered over with CGI? There are actors that have no layer of CGI on them but it's not a live action film if you just over-insert CGI throughout the film.  The film looks good, I could have wished I were born earlier so that I could work alongside the production team and experience the real work and effort for myself because this film looks like a passion project and I want to see it from concept to final...I can dream...

text: The description says it's based on a Manga named "Gunnm" but to me it's typical Tekken guys! I mean the first glance after seeing the whole trailer I was like "wtf they're making a live action adaptation of globally acclaimed game like Tekken and not giving Namco a credit??!!!" text: Both James Camerons and Robert Rodriguez are stupid.   The reason Alita has big eyes in the manga is that manga is drawn at a million miles per hour. The drawings are crude. Rather than use nuanced drawings to depict emotion or character, artists use shorthand symbolism. Alita's big eyes mean she's naive, good-natured, not evil, etc.  A live action film is not crude. You can use nuanced acting to depict Alita's good nature.  To replicate the big eyes in a live action shows not only a fundamental misunderstanding of Battle Angel Alita but an equal misunderstanding of manga.  This is not a movie by fans. This is a movie by poseurs. The best trailer in world couldn't make me buy a ticket. This movie will be heartless.
